      "response_length": 92,
      "response": "\n\nA phoneme is the smallest unit of sound in a language that can distinguish meaning between words, functioning as an abstract representation of speech sounds categorized by their functional role rather than physical articulation. Key principles include contrastiveness, which creates minimal pairs (like /p/ and /b/ in \"pat\" and \"bat\"), complementary distribution where allophones are context-dependent variants, and phonological rules governing phoneme realization. Phonemes are central to phonological analysis, enabling description of sound systems, language acquisition research, orthography development, and applications in speech recognition technology, language teaching, and clinical speech disorder assessment.",
